Here is a Java solution to determine if a given integer is a power of three:

```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        while (n % 3 == 0) {
            n /= 3;
        }
        return n == 1;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Test cases
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(9)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(12)); // false
    }
}
```

This solution checks if the given integer `n` is a power of three by continuously dividing it by 3 until it is no longer divisible by 3. If the final result is 1, then `n` is a power of three, otherwise, it is not.

The follow-up question asks if the solution can be solved without loops or recursion. Here is an alternative solution using logarithms:

```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        double logResult = Math.log(n) / Math.log(3);
        return Math.abs(logResult - Math.round(logResult)) < 1e-10;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Test cases
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(9)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(12)); // false
    }
}
```

This solution uses the logarithm property that log_a(b) = log_c(b) / log_c(a) to calculate the logarithm of `n` with base 3. If the result is an integer (within a small tolerance to account for floating-point precision errors), then `n` is a power of three.

